# Language split — code vs UI

The dev team works in **English only** for everything in the repository except end-user Arabic copy.

## English only

- Source code identifiers (variables, functions, types, file names)
- **All comments** (`//`, `/* */`, JSDoc, block headers in `.ts`, `.tsx`, `.mjs`, `.go`, etc.)
- **Console / log / stderr** messages in scripts and Electron main (developer-facing)
- **Git commit messages** and PR descriptions
- **Cursor rules** and internal docs aimed at developers
- README technical sections (user-facing Arabic marketing copy is optional elsewhere)

## Arabic only

- `src/locales/ar.json` and any future locale files
- User-visible strings in the React UI (via `t("…")` / i18n keys)
- Arabic **test fixture data** when explicitly testing Arabic search or RTL behavior (not comments)

## Do not

- Mix Arabic into code comments or commit messages
- Hard-code Arabic UI strings in components when a translation key exists
- Add Arabic explanations in scripts (`bump-version`, `git-ship`, etc.)

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
/** قائمة الحسابات الموحّدة */

// ✅ GOOD
/** Unified accounts list with due progress bar */
```

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
console.log("[ship] تمّ push");

// ✅ GOOD
console.log("[ship] pushed to current branch");
```

```bash
# ❌ BAD
git commit -m "إصلاح الصفحة الرئيسية"

# ✅ GOOD
git commit -m "fix(home): reorganize stats into tabs"
```

When touching legacy Arabic comments or logs, translate them to English in the same change.
